"He was a Man." When He lay in the back of that boat that night, with ten thousand devils of the sea swearing they would drown Him, the winds howling, the mast broken, and the oars lost, the little ship was waterlogged and plunging. The devil was lightning gleaming on top of every wave, his eyes glistening, saying, "I've got Him now." He was a Man laying in the back of that boat, undisturbed by the winds and waves, sleeping, tired like any other man. 
But when He put His foot upon the brail of the boat, looked up, and said, "Peace, be still," and the winds and waves obeyed Him, that was more than a man. That was Deity speaking through Him.
It is true that He was a Man when He cried on the cross, "My God, why hast Thou forsaken Me?" He was a Man hanging there on the cross, but when He arose on Easter morning, breaking the Roman seal and opening the tomb, He proved He was God.
As the poet said:
Living, He loved me;
Dying, He saved me;
Buried, He carried my sins far away;
Rising, He justified freely forever:
Someday He's coming--oh, glorious day.
